= Let Yourself Be Free

...a fine point that I think is useful for those of you who are traversing this great mountain of awakening.
And I’m just a Sherpa, right?---who's guiding you to the top of the mountain, where you already stand, ironically.
So we’ll pretend like we’re going to the bottom and going up, 'cause we’ve already been at the apex, at the summit, and we’re here.

The recognition of the nature of mind allows you to access that primordial purity of this presence, so no story can get ahold of you and displace you from that perfection.
Yeah, it really takes some kind of subscription, some kind of wanting some sense desire, we can’t have it, so the purely present perfection is then tainted; it’s displaced.

But here I want to mention something that might be useful.
As you’re traversing up this mountain, like I was just discussing with [Sangha member], once you start to reach the top, you know, like in Mount Everest, the oxygen starts to run out?
Once you get past this certain level, there is nobody anymore to be enlightened, for that was just conditioned consciousness, like we see in the five aggregates in the Buddhadharma.
When that conditioned self, that manas-vijnana as they call it in Sanskrit, when that softens up, that sphere of electromagnetic contraction, of empty energy, when that lightens up, well, where is the one...?

For example, if… I can even speak from… using these words like “I” and “me”, and “myself”.
So if I sit here and say “I’m abiding in pure presence,” it’s more “I’m abiding as pure presence.”
And, I don’t want to play verbal gymnastics, right?
So we can just speak about this, and make sure people are accessing, but if I say “I’m pure presence,” there’s nothing apprehending that anymore.  

We have this micromanager in spirituality and the contemplative practices.
When that starts to fall off, and you don’t care anymore… you don’t even… you almost feel guilty, because you don’t feel spiritual or religious anymore, but you’re doing all this… sacred stuff.
Everything’s sacred.
Literally, the dog poop is as sacred as a golden Buddha statue.
Precisely that.

And if we don’t just maintain the status quo of this environment: “Oh yeah, everything’s luminosity,”---but then we just buckle back into reification of and the crystallization of the elements, and this material dream…

It could be our time, and we are a tribe, you know.
We’re—you’ve never seen a tribe like this.
We are the online tribe now.
And tribes have been prophesied to come—awakened tribes.
That’s us.
We are here.  

So, to let yourself be free.  To really entertain the fact that this environment… that we’re crystallizing a dream, we’re subscribing to it, we’re obsessed with it.

And then, when you’re a practitioner, samsara’s doing anything to get your attention, isn’t it?  “Ooh, I’m free and spacious.”  Here comes the lovely partner, or you know, some… I don’t know what you’re into, dude, girl, in-between… I’m not into anything, so I don’t chase any of these things, so please pardon my language, but… you know:  “I’m free and clear”—all the sudden you see this person.  It’s an aggregate, created by your mind.  And it says “C’mere, I want your attention.”  

All the sudden your stomach starts… you know, another situation, your stomach starts getting that feeling; people, everybody says it’s hunger—it’s not hunger, it’s just your stomach clearing out.  But you start getting hungry, or maybe you’re really getting hungry,—then watch how quick you snap  back to that sense world; it’s getting your attention.  I’m not saying go hungry, but this is kind of what happens. 

There’ll be somebody who emails you with some drama; they’re just trying to get your attention.  That’s samsara, trying to get your attention.  And every time you bite the hook… uhhuh?  You’re biting the hook, and it’s okay; it’s happening within our knowingness.

(Dawai reads from the chat)
So [Sangha 1]’s asking:  “Do we forget to ask ‘Who’s the one who’s desirous?’”

Well, I don’t recommend that; I’ve said that several times, that I don’t recommend that as a practice, because you’d have to train yourself to say it, and you’d have to repeat it at certain… I think it can come naturally when you repeat it, when you say that to yourself.  Let it come naturally, if it comes naturally.  A lot of people…

The problem with these little phrases, these inquiry phrases, is that they get repetitive, and our mind hates repetition.  It loves it in terms of crystallizing reality, but it hates it—even in terms of crystallizing reality, we get bored so easy with this majestic world you know, that our mind is creating; we get bored so easy with it, when things get crystallized and repetitive.   So, this is really the case, you know.  If a phrase like “look at the one who’s thinking”… if you use that too much, it won’t do anything.  

So that’s why we really hinge on awareness to brighten you up, to freshen you up, to activate emptiness.  To activate the full majesty of this….what they call reality, but it’s just absolute truth.  So we hinge on awareness, because that’s the one thing in this whole scene that’s pure right now, that we know is pure and uncontrived, is this clear light awareness.  That’s why pointing out can be so significant, so special.  

And your clear light mind has always been here with you, it will always be here with you.  It has always protected you even as you’re going through your own mind’s creations.  It has been there, gently waiting for harmonization.  

Making sense so far, everybody?  I really encourage you—it may seem tempting to hold this micromanager, this one that says “Oh, this is where I’m  at now, and this anger has fallen off, this sadness has gone away, this hurt is …No!  That’s a trick!  As long as you’re managing the hurt, the hurt is still there.  So as long as you’re saying, “Oh, my hurt is pretty much gone now,” no, it’s not, because you’re still holding it.  

So this would be like having a Blob in your hand (Dawai demonstrates holding something in his hand) and trying to satisfy this Blob constantly.  

When the Blob’s gone, it’s gone.  (Dawai looks down, pretending his hand is now empty of Blobs), and you say “Wow, the Blob’s gone.”  (Dawai looks away from his empty hand)
 
Boom!  The blob’s back there. (Dawai looks at the invisible Blob, back in his hand again; it’s speaking.)

BLOB:  Did you see that? I was gone for a second!

DAWAI: The Blob’s now talking.

BLOB:  I was gone for a second!  I felt spacious, and I was free, and it was ineffable…

DAWAI: (he looks down and speaks to the Blob) Wow, Blob, great job!

This is the conditioned self.  It has moments of release, and then it comes back into its contraction.  And it says, “Look what I did!”

So maybe we can say the consciousness gets small, and it’s like “I’m experiencing spaciousness,” after it was just like this (Dawai holds his hands spread wide apart), right?  It’s nice and spacious and everything—wow, enlightened! Then it goes fwoom! (Dawai brings his hands back together) :  “Wow, I’m enlightened!  Did you see me being enlightened, everybody?”

Making sense, yeah?

(Dawai addresses someone wanting to speak) Yes, please!

SANGHA 1:  I just found that so relatable, because often, you know, when I’m in awareness, I often, so often, it’s kind of annoying, it happens so often, where it’s like literally, the idea of like awareness just pops in my mind, and it just, I can just, it is, I’m just pulled back, and I know it’s like “awareness”, or “there it is”, or something silly like that, and you know, I…

DAWAI:  it’s the micromanager.

SANGHA 1 Yeah, yeah, yeah… I guess what I’m gonna ask  is like, it’s kind of a hurdle in my… it’s something that happens to me, is what I’m saying, so I can totally relate to what you’re talking about right now. Yeah.

DAWAI:  Oh yeah.  And please don’t feel alone.  This is sort of common psychology.  And seeing it is enough.  Just seeing.  “Wow, I’m evaluating empty energy right now.”  You know. Or whatever. 

(Dawai addresses another sangha member wanting to speak) Yes, so, Sangha 2, yeah.

SANGHA 2:  It’s interesting to observe how I start to frame what I’m going to say before it’s my turn to speak.  Just that, literally talking about the micromanager, talking about kind of like the administrative mind, going on to say “I, I, I, I lost, I feel like like I, like it’s dwindled a little bit,” … boom! There you go, pay attention, boy!

Yeah, when it comes to the hurt that is caused, right?  Lately I’ve been kind of like—comes in bouts, really, but you know, sometimes I just get really pissed off about kinda like what happened in my last relationship.  And it’s, and obviously I don’t want to feel like this, ‘cause in the end, you know, blah blah blah, important person in my life, taught me so many lessons, blah blah blah blah blah.  And I try to pay attention to it just like as I kinda like as I kinda like have the thoughts kinda like scream out, kinda like and…
I don’t know if it’s pride, or shame, or like just pure hurt over what happened.  It still pops up every now and again.  I think not too long ago I had a dream.  Like, I might have mentioned it.  And I just, I woke up and I was in a bad mood.  I felt like I had been like rejected over and over again during the dream.  In fact that’s what basically happened.
And I guess, yeah, I’ve been trying to just observe it, you know, whenever I’ve got the self-awareness to look at my… kinda like to see my thoughts without really being right in them.  But it’s… it’s what’s … that’s what’s for dinner tonight,I guess.

DAWAI:  Well, thank you for sharing that, and I deeply empathize with that feeling of rejection. And you can get that from parental influences, relationship influences, cultural, societal influences… Yeah.  That’s real stuff there.  But I promise you, there’s something very very special in that hurt, in that feeling of rejection, when you stop calling it a feeling of rejection.  Just leave it at raw energy, raw experience, pure perfection… and you’ll be so happy that you feel tender enough to love, to miss somebody.  Your heart is there.  Our tenderness can be reconciled.  And safe.  Yeah, we don’t need to be vulnerable in our tenderness, our compassion, our empathy.  

Right now you’re feeling vulnerable in that.  And that’s, of course, normal.  
But if you can trust me a little bit here, remember, you don’t have to try to put any of this in awareness; it’s there.  You’re just more used to being in the hurt than you are in the spaciousness.  The spacious knowingness is always there, like this camera, you know, I joke around.  It’s like this camera that’s on.  It has a knowingness permeating everything, all the time.  You can’t get rid of that.  But you can be disorientated.  Because it’s very heavy to be in our sadness, right?  We can anchor down into that quite easily.

(Dawai reads from the chat) I said that a long time ago, long time ago, Yeshe, you got the year on that too, that’s three years ago!  Bringing back quotes that I said from three years ago.  “Rejection is protection.”  Yeshe, do you remember the story behind that one?  I learned that mantra from a little girl.  These two twins, they were like talking about how some boy didn’t smile at them or something, and they were like, “It’s okay,” and they said at the same time “because rejection is protection!”. I was like “Yeah, right on… Sounds good to me!”  Yeah, so I did not invent that saying.

So, this is the case though; there’s a mighty tenderness that we tend to run from.  It feels vulnerable.  Even the tears beginning to come down our face can be scary.
So please, my friends, I invite you to reconcile your tenderness, okay?

Alright, so I think Sangha 3 also wanted to join in there.

SANGHA 3:  Feels like a theme, for like at least the last two sessions or so:  distraction, being in the mind’s hurts, and definitely has been a theme for me, because whoa, I was like totally taken over, last session and also this session, I was just totally in the story, for the short sits, and through the sessions, very little, you know, attention span, things like that.  Kept going in and out.  And of course I’m not making myself wrong for it, ‘cause I recognize, you know, how often I’ve done that, but still, yeah.  And I see as well, like you know, I thought maybe it’s just me or the weather, or I hope I’m not bringing it to the weather of the group, because I see in the sharings people are always like clear in the sharings, and suddenly everyone is sharing like this (he looks away towards the side) and our Lama Dawai has to be like “Yo, look at me when you talk!”, and stuff like that.  Yeah, and I’m really noticing, I’m like seeing as a reflection also of my own state and you know, own distractedness and stuff like that.  And even more than that I’m also seeing how, you know, my lifestyle as well, you know, it’s like when I do more dharma stuff all these things is not so much of a, you know, issue.  It’s like a protection.  Whereas if I’m like and I’m still doing a lot of sensual pleasures and stuff, so I’m like “Errr,” whether to get in or not, and then I get in anyway, and you are there, and it’s like I’m in a certain state, and then my theory?  doesn’t come off.  So I’m seeing all of that. And I’m very present to all of that, and I’m sort of just letting myself be okay with that.
And hurts, as well!  Gosh, I have so many hurts, and it’s like I’m always trying… well so, I mean I don’t have much going on now, but like when I was like, you know, still at my job and stuff like that, always struggling with all the like group dynamics, social expectations, unsaid things. And sometimes it’s not that unsaid, like they will say it, you know, and not so nicely, ‘cause it’s like “you should already know this,” you know.  And it’s like, you know… So it’s like I felt very, I realized that I still felt very hurt by it.  But of course, every time I’m triggered, I’m like, you know, “don’t go make a fight with people, if they don’t get you, or what, it’s okay just to be nice and deal with it later.”  And I guess now is the later, where it’s like all the hurts are coming out, all the stories.  And of course, I know it’s just a story, but, and I let the echo out, but sometimes it’s like Aargh, you know; sometimes like if a person is…

DAWAI:  Whoa, whoa, whoa, wait a minute.  It’s not just a story when it’s hurt.  Stories initiated that hurt, and welled it up, and compounded that hurt.  Stories maintained that hurt.  But that hurt when it’s coming up, when it’s reversing—now it’s coming up for you.

SANGHA 3: Yeah.

DAWAI:  So for example, if I think about Little Man, my cat, right? I could, well especially, like, a year ago, I could think of Little Man—that’s the story, right?  But the feeling, of me missing the little cat that I had for 18 years, you know, that’s fine.  That’s normal.  And then the story starts to fall away, and then we only have this, you know.
And that is your bond, you know, for example, with your family, your ancestors, who are so-called “dead.”  That is your bond there.  That is your connection.  That is why we don’t want to … So you have some work connection there, perhaps even ancestral lineage with your co-workers, you know, some in your mandala, and things like that.  And so, without the story what is there?  Right?  The story is sort of secondary.
So the hurt’s not just a story, it’s hurt and a story.  Is that making sense?

SANGHA 3:  Yeah.  It makes sense.  And to be clear, don’t know if I didn’t phrase it right, but definitely I wasn’t like cheapening my hurt, I was just letting it be.  But maybe I’m like criticizing myself too much for, you know,  being in the story and stuff like that, so…  But I definitely still have more work to do, because I’m always proliferating, always narrating, but I’m getting more and more okay with that, getting more and more… less and less criticizing myself for being a bad practitioner for you know just narrating and narrating.  That’s just how my mind is, but…Yeah, thank you for clarification as well, and for the space and opportunity, even if I spend a lot of it getting distracted, hopefully that wears off after a while.  Have to listen, to try to actually listen to people and be with people, too, man, and just be patient. Yeah.

DAWAI:  Oh, you’re so perfect, Sangha 3, you don’t worry about a thing.
But how is your time off going?

SANGHA 3:  Aaah, just been chilling, enjoying a long long weekend.  Doing my usual stuff…

DAWAI:  Good.

SANGHA 3:  … yes, dharma…

DAWAI:  Does it feel different, not working?  Like mentally and everything?

SANGHA 3:  Uh, yeah I think so, but I’ve been getting used to it now, and it was a long process. I also took, you know, when I handed in my resignation I took like an extra long notice period and the replacement came early, so I guess I’ve been marinating in the chill for a bit.  But still when… it took awhile to sink in, and at first it literally felt like a long weekend, and I guess it still does, you know, but after a while certain things came up, and I guess it’s still part of the process right now.

DAWAI:  Wow.  That’s amazing.  I’m glad you have that space for those things to come up.  Yeah, man.  It sounds like it, anyway.  You have a nice, good environment right now for this.

SANGHA 3:  Yeah, I’m glad too, and your guidance, you know, and the Sangha, coming to sessions, doing a lot of dharma helps as well.  So that’s so, yeah, I’m appreciative, and I’ll see if I can be kinder to myself as well.

DAWAI:  Yeah, you know, “just a story,” it’s like an implicit nihilism.  You know, when we start to get into that “writing it off” type of quick-minded sense of… You know, the stories are also very very precious, so I think it’s a good reminder for all of us.  
You know, that, yeah, we talk about the narration and the stories and the labels, but those are very very precious, too.  Yeah, this is a whole world that opens up for us, once, you know… and it’s a whole new world.  (Dawai starts to sing) It’s a whole—no, not gonna do that.

SANGHA 2:  I was gonna join in!

DAWAI:  You guys are just as crazy as me, that’s why. 

SANGHA 3:  A chorus that’s coming up from our mics…

DAWAI:  Goodness.  Well, thank you for that; it’s always so good to hear from you.  

Yeah, and remember, just as a warning, that, as you activate, as you liberate, you go into renunciation; they’re synonymous.  And you know, the stuff that you were drawn to, previously, may not be drawing you in anymore.  That’s just part of it.  And it may even seem boring, because you’re no longer stimulated.  And it may even seem like there’s a space to fill there, when something falls away.  So all that is totally normal, so to speak, in regards to how liberation looks.

Full renunciation—you’d rather have it happen while you’re alive, than when you’re dead or dying, trust me.  So, and it also provides a lot of freedom there. 

(Dawai notices a comment in chat) [Sangha member] says,”Why?”  

Because, when you’re incapacitated for example, say you’re sick or you’re dying, you’re not gonna be able to get ahold of your sense pleasures, for example cigarettes.  You’re really, your mind is addicted to cigarettes and wants one very very badly, and you can’t even move your arm.  Right?… at some point.  You’re not even gonna be able to access a cigarette, and your mind’s gonna be suffering badly. So it’s better to have renunciation while you’re still alive.  Free your mind.  And the thing is, you could free your mind while you’re smoking, even.

Or you can be… Well, some kids, they have drug… they’re like, since they’re babies they have the strong nicotine, or strong cocaine, or crack or something, or alcohol in them, so even for them liberation is possible.  Maybe they cannot, you know, get rid of that cocaine in their bodies, part of their chemistry, because their mother was on it, right?  Even for them, salvation is accessible.  

You know, this isn’t about balancing your energies—which is a great part of it.  It happens.  But if I had one arm—or even worse, one ear—then I’d be off balance, in terms of, you know, what we see, what appears.  In regards to dzogchen, you can still have total balance, even with one ear. And we don’t prioritize what the physical body is doing.  That’s made clear in the anuyoga scriptures, explicitly clear.  

It’s great, you know; you get all these benefits, and sort of side-effects of dzogchen, of using the awareness practice.  And that’s what’s gonna hold up the material world for a while; they’re gonna use meta-awareness to become better at the material world.  That’s gonna be the great conundrum for a while there.  It’s not gonna be until physicists, and you know, like Donald Hoffman, can prove it to the world, that this is a dream.  You’re trying to get better at a dream.   And once people have that explicitly in their face, then they can finally see, but it’s usually… they have to go through a whole life before they learn that lesson, that there’s a futility here.  That there’s an emptiness to it all.  

Yeah, and I think that, for practitioners, that’s what’s so special about all of you people.  You reach for it before your life ends.  And many people that are on drugs and on alcohol, they just have never met with dzogchen.  They have never met with a path.  So they go to the drugs, they go to the alcohol. Because they know there’s something about this life that’s a kind of, you know, illusion.  There’s something not right about it.

And then you start subscribing to somebody else’s reality, based on somebody else’s desires, and their power, their want to control, and things like that.  And so we start living by somebody else’s standards, pretty  quickly.  Yeah.

So anyway, it’s quite special to begin to integrate the environment into our practice, just as much as thoughts, and emotions.  Allowing yourself to be free, recognizing when that self-troping goes on, and we say “I’ll be enlightened next lifetime,”or “I’m not a buddha ,” or something.  

This pure presence is it, right now.  All of you, right now, are buddhas.  (Dawai pauses)  Yeah.  There’s nothing wrong, really.  Nowhere to go, nothing to figure out… 

I should be careful; I might not have a job anymore, if I keep talking like this.  

Okay, everyone.  Well, that’s my little sharing today, little dharma talk sharing, and I really appreciate those of you who stayed a little extra time and hung out here.  I know that you got things to do, and you have a whole life, so it’s great that you’re spending it with the dharma.

And you know, many of you who are at the summit with me, and have been with me for a while now—just really, understand that, you know, if you were a cup of tea, like some foul tea or something, mixed with water, once you recognize awareness, it’s like recognizing the wetness.  And that’s the pure aspect.  That tea starts to go away, and you’re left with pure water.  So you become sort of a renunciate, okay?  You may not be inclined towards the sense world.  

The sense world will still be trying to get you—trust me.  It might try to get you five different ways in two different days, I don’t know.  But, and it comes at you many different ways.   

And, as awareness practitioners, what’s powerful is, you can let yourself get hooked.  And you become a Trojan Horse, for samsara.   Because, you know, these demons brought you into their clubhouse, but they didn’t know awareness was with you.  So it’s like a stink bomb for them—it goes off in the clubhouse.  And this is what you’re doing—you’re bringing 
your friend awareness secretly with you into that habit.  Yeah.  

Ok, any final comments, questions, anything, before we check out today?   (Dawai pauses) 

All right, good, everybody gonna be all right, huh?  Okay, yeah, thank you, thank you.
(Dawai responds to a chat) Yes, Sangha 4, we can.

And then, don’t forget, I’ll mention this here and there, I suppose:  we have a retreat coming up this weekend, where we’re just gonna go into the view, we’re gonna summit this mountain.  We’re gonna take some of these people from Dharmachanics up the mountain.  And it’s gonna happen—all of them.  Every one of them’s gonna be free—anybody who joins this retreat.  We insist upon it!  
All right, very good.  (Dawai reads the chat)  Yeah, “Or your money back.”  There’s no money, Sangha 5!

There’s a zoom link.  Yeshe, maybe post that zoom link one more time for people.  I just want to make sure those of you who have been so diligent and practicing together, you know, that we all get a chance to be there.  
And come and go as you… I know that Dharmachanics is a little more structured and stuff like that, but I would say come and go as you can.  If you can be there the full 3-hour sessions—because what will happen is, we’ll have a 3-hour session, then a half an hour break, then another 3-hour session on Saturday.  Then on Sunday we’ll have a 3-hour session, a half an hour break, then another 3-hour session.  If you can make all of the hours, of course that’s great.
Okay.  (Dawai sees the zoom link in the chat) And there is the “Main Dharma Hall”.  I love that Ron [founder of Dharmachanics] calls it the “Dharma Hall”—that’s great.  And of course Ron seems like a really stand-up guy.  

Okay.  Yeah.

SANGHA 4: I watched—there’s a YouTube video of Ron being interviewed, and the way he described his group sounds so much like this group, and the way that their group came about, and the way that you’ve talked about how this group has grown, and how there wasn’t really any structure, or he wasn’t sure if the whole doing it online would work, so it’s very interesting to see the kind of connections between the two groups.  

DAWAI:  Our group is actually a little more structured than his—believe it or not.  I thought we were the wild ones.  But yeah, because we adhere to a teaching.  You know, they try different flavors of teachings.  Some groups are like that.  But we adhere pretty much to…

(Dawai sees a comment in chat) Oh yeah, Sangha 6, good to have you back.  You stay good up there in the North... (I didn’t want to dox him.)  

Okay, so.  Let’s end— I really want to continue this, especially with those of you who are becoming more powerful, you know.  I’m not gonna, you know, sugar-coat that.  You’re becoming more powerful.  
And, so please let’s rest here, in this pure presence, and do a dedication.  All these beings are here with us, all these world leaders—there are beings that are alone, that are sick, confused, injured… let’s just dedicate everything, all this open-hearted presence, to them.  
(Dawai pauses) 
Ah, yeah.  Deep, deep bow to you, my friends.  Have a beautiful day.  Take care, okay?

